context_meta.title: Mark Hamill on why Luke's 'Empire Strikes Back' scream 'makes no sense'
context_meta.summary: When George Lucas released his Special Edition versions of the three original Star Wars films in theaters in 1997, there was an equally horrifying — and, frankly, confusing — change put in. The moment in question occurred in The Empire Strikes Back where Darth Vader has just cut off Luke's hand and revealed that the dark lord of the Sith is actually Luke's father. In the original film released in 1980, a panicked Luke considers the offer, then collects himself, pauses, and then calmly chooses death over the dark side, letting go and allowing himself to fall into the Bespin abyss. It's a powerful moment of ultimate sacrifice — and one that was then ruined when Lucas nonsensically decided to add a cowardly scream to Luke's descent.
